#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:23
msgid "When did you begin training in Daito Ryu Aiki Jujutsu?"
msgstr "Quand avez-vous commenc&eacute; &agrave; pratiquer le Daito Ryu Aiki Jujutsu?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:24
msgid ""
"I was about 21 years old when I started training with\n"
"                Takuma Hisa Sensei. So it was in 1970."
msgstr "J'avais environ 21 ans lorsque j'ai commenc&eacute; &agrave; m'entra&icirc;ner avec Takuma Hisa Sensei. C'&eacute;tait donc en 1970."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:27
msgid ""
"Why did you stop your karate training and how did you\n"
"                begin your training in Daito Ryu?"
msgstr "Pourquoi avez-vous cess&eacute; de pratiquer le karat&eacute; et comment avez-vous commenc&eacute; votre pratique du Daito Ryu? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:29
msgid ""
"There was an incident I had with some a Yakuza fellow.\n"
"                I was out one night with my girlfriend, and he started being rude\n"
"                to her. I intervened and asked him to stop, after which he became\n"
"                aggressive and attacked me with a bokuto. Since I practiced karate,\n"
"                I was quiet strong with my fists and knew I could make a serious\n"
"                injury if I punched but I did not want to hurt him badly, so all\n"
"                I could do is block the strikes of the stick with my arms. Finally\n"
"                he gave up and left me alone. However, after this fight my arms\n"
"                were swollen and hurting for two months. After this incident I\n"
"                thought hard to myself, what if that was a sword and not a stick\n"
"                I was attacked with, I would have lost my arms. So I began to\n"
"                search for a martial art that would teach me how to defeat the\n"
"                sword. After about a year of looking for a school I came across\n"
"                Hisa Takuma Sensei's group, I found the things they were practicing\n"
"                very interesting, Hisa Sensei had traditional technique so I asked\n"
"                him if I could study under him. He accepted me and so I began\n"
"                my training."
msgstr "J'ai eu une altercation avec un homme de Yakuza. J'&eacute;tais sorti un soir avec ma copine et il a  commenc&eacute; &agrave; &ecirc;tre impoli avec elle.  Je suis intervenu et lui ai demand&eacute; d'arr&ecirc;ter, apr&egrave;s quoi il a commenc&eacute; &agrave; &ecirc;tre agressif et &agrave; m'attaquer avec un bokuto.  Comme je pratiquais le karat&eacute;, j'&eacute;tais tr&egrave;s fort avec mes poings et je savais que je pouvais causer des blessures s&eacute;rieuses si je le frappais, mais je ne voulais pas le blesser gravement, alors tout ce que j'ai fais, c'est bloquer ses attaques au b&acirc;ton avec mes bras.  &agrave; la fin, il finit par abandonner et &agrave; me laisser tranquille.  Par contre, apr&egrave;s cette bagarre, mes bras &eacute;taient enfl&eacute;s et m'ont fait mal pendant deux mois.  Suite &agrave; cet incident, j'ai beaucoup r&eacute;fl&eacute;chi: et si &#231;a avait &eacute;t&eacute; une &eacute;p&eacute;e plut&ocirc;t qu'un b&acirc;ton, j'en aurais perdu mes bras!  J'ai donc commenc&eacute; &agrave; chercher un art martial qui pourrait m'apprendre &agrave; combattre et d&eacute;faire une &eacute;p&eacute;e.  Apr&egrave;s environ un an de recherche, j'ai rencontr&eacute; le groupe de Hisa Takuma Sensei.  J'ai trouv&eacute; que ce qu'ils pratiquaient &eacute;tait tr&egrave;s int&eacute;ressant, Hisa Sensei avait des techniques traditionnelles, alors je lui ai demand&eacute; si je pouvais &eacute;tudier sous sa supervision.  Il a accept&eacute; et j'ai commenc&eacute; mon entra&icirc;nement."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:47
msgid "How long did you train with Hisa Sensei?"
msgstr "Combien de temps avez-vous pratiqu&eacute; avec Hisa Sensei? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:48
msgid ""
"I trained under him until the late seventies, up to\n"
"                the point when Hisa Sensei became frail and his son asked him\n"
"                to move to Tokyo so he could take care of him."
msgstr "J'ai pratiqu&eacute; avec lui jusqu'&agrave; la fin des ann&eacute;es soixante-dix, jusqu'&agrave; ce que Hisa Sensei s'affaiblisse et que son fils lui demande d'emm&eacute;nager avec lui  &agrave; Tokyo pour qu'il puisse s'en occuper."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:52
msgid "How was your training with Hisa Sensei?"
msgstr "Comment &eacute;tait votre pratique avec Hisa Sensei?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:53
msgid ""
"With time Hisa Sensei became frail and he could not\n"
"                move very well. So he would usually teach by speaking and explaining\n"
"                how to do the movements, and demonstrating them slowly. Senior\n"
"                students of Hisa Sensei's and me came together and formed what\n"
"                is now know as the Takumakai, and practiced the techniques, working\n"
"                them out under Hisa Sensei's direction. The training was good\n"
"                and we worked hard. At the same time I felt there was something\n"
"                missing in the movements, there was some element that wasn't there.\n"
"                I endured these feelings and continued my training. After this\n"
"                period Hisa Sensei moved to Tokyo upon request of his son. So\n"
"                his son would be able to take care of him. When this happened\n"
"                I was going to quit my training. So I went to see Hisa Sensei\n"
"                to ask him his permission to quit. When I told him of my feelings,\n"
"                he told me 'no, you must continue to practice, I will introduce\n"
"                you to a very good teacher', and wrote me a letter of recommendation\n"
"                to go see Takeda Tokimune Sensei in Hokkaido."
msgstr "Avec le temps, Hisa Sensei est devenu plus faible et il ne pouvait plus bouger correctement.  Alors il enseignait en parlant et en expliquant comment ex&eacute;cuter les mouvements et en faisant de lentes d&eacute;monstrations.  Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves seniors de Hisa Sensei et moi avons donc cr&eacute;&eacute; ce qui est maintenant connu sous le nom du Takumakai et nous pratiquions les techniques sous la supervision de Hisa Sensei.  La pratique &eacute;tait bonne et nous travaillions fort.  Par contre, en m&ecirc;me temps, je sentais qu'il y avait quelque chose qui manquait dans les mouvements, qu'il y avait des &eacute;l&eacute;ments qui n'&eacute;taient pas l&agrave;.  J'ai r&eacute;prim&eacute; ces pens&eacute;es et continu&eacute; mon entra&icirc;nement.  Apr&egrave;s cette p&eacute;riode, Hisa Sensei a d&eacute;m&eacute;nag&eacute; &agrave; Tokyo selon la volont&eacute; de son fils qui voulait en prendre soin.  Lorsque cela s'est produit, j'&eacute;tais pr&ecirc;t &agrave; abandonner la pratique.  J'ai donc &eacute;t&eacute; voir Hisa Sensei pour lui demander la permission d'arr&ecirc;ter.  Lorsque je lui ai expliqu&eacute; ma pens&eacute;e, il m'a dit : ' non.  Tu dois continuer &agrave; pratiquer, je vais te pr&eacute;senter &agrave; un tr&egrave;s bon professeur ', et il m'a &eacute;crit une lettre de recommandation pour aller rencontrer Takeda Tokimune Sensei &agrave; Hokkaido."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:70
msgid "When did you receive your kyoju dairi from Hisa Sensei?"
msgstr "Quand avez-vous re&#231;u votre kyoju dairi de Hisa Sensei?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:71
msgid "I received it in 1976."
msgstr "Je l'ai re&#231;u en 1976. "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:73
msgid ""
"So after the recommendation from Hisa Sensei, you went\n"
"                to train with Takeda Sensei?"
msgstr "Donc, suite &agrave; la recommandation de Hisa Sensei, vous avez &eacute;t&eacute; pratiqu&eacute; avec Takeda Sensei?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:75
msgid ""
"That's correct. I went to Abashiri, Hokkaido to learn\n"
"                from Takeda Sensei. From him at first I learned basic techniques,\n"
"                the shoden. The Takumakai did not have these basic ones; they\n"
"                practiced more advanced waza."
msgstr "Effectivement.  Je me suis rendu &agrave; Abashiri, &agrave; Hokkaido, pour suivre les enseignements de Takeda Sensei. De lui, au d&eacute;but, j'ai appris les techniques de base, le shoden. Le Takumakai ne poss&eacute;dait pas ces techniques, on pratiquait davantage les waza avanc&eacute;s."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:80
msgid "When did you first meet Takeda Sensei?"
msgstr "Quand avez-vous rencontr&eacute; pour la premi&egrave;re fois Takeda Sensei? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:81
msgid "Twenty five years ago, so it must have been 1977."
msgstr "Il y a 25 ans, c'&eacute;tait donc en 1977."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:83
msgid "So at that time you were part of the Takumakai?"
msgstr "Donc, &agrave; ce moment, vous faisiez partie du Takumakai? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:84
msgid ""
"That's correct. Because I went with to study under Soke\n"
"                (Takeda Tokimune Sensei) with Hisa Sensei's recommendation, in\n"
"                Japanese thinking it was as if I was learning from both teachers\n"
"                at the same time. I took the shoden waza and brought them back\n"
"                to the Takumakai."
msgstr "Effectivement.  Parce que j'y avais &eacute;t&eacute; pour &eacute;tudier avec le Soke (Takeda Tokimune Sensei) avec la recommandation de Hisa Sensei, dans la mentalit&eacute; japonaise c'&eacute;tait comme d'apprendre de deux professeurs en m&ecirc;me temps.  J'ai pris le shoden waza et l'ai ramen&eacute; au Takumakai."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:90
msgid "How was your training with Takeda Sensei?"
msgstr "Comment &eacute;tait votre entra&icirc;nement avec Takeda Sensei? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:91
msgid ""
"I was in pretty fit shape at that time because I did\n"
"                a lot of skiing and played a lot of soccer. Although feeling strong,\n"
"                I put myself on a 100-day program before going to see Soke (Takeda\n"
"                Sensei) to prepare myself for training with him. When I went to\n"
"                see him, I was fortunate because Soke quit his work right before\n"
"                I got there. We would have one on one training in the morning,\n"
"                from 5 A.m. to 8 A.m., then a break until lunch, more one on one\n"
"                training after lunch until the evening. And then there was an\n"
"                evening class with other students. The first morning I came to\n"
"                the dojo at 5, and Soke was already there, so the next day I decided\n"
"                to come 15 minutes earlier, at 4:45, to be there before Takeda\n"
"                Sensei. The following day, I came to the dojo at 4:45 and Soke\n"
"                was already there. So, next morning I showed up at 4:15, and getting\n"
"                there before Soke I felt some pride about this. However, the next\n"
"                day, I came at 4:15 and Soke was there before me again. I did\n"
"                not know the reason for this, but this continued to go on until\n"
"                we started training at 3 A.m. At this point, Takeda Sensei's wife\n"
"                came out and said to me, 'You can't come into the dojo before\n"
"                Soke, he needs his time to train and it is the only time he can\n"
"                train by himself before teaching.'"
msgstr "J'&eacute;tais en bonne forme &agrave; l'&eacute;poque parce que j'avais fait beaucoup de ski et jouait beaucoup au soccer.  Bien que je me sentais fort, je me suis quand m&ecirc;me mis sur un programme de 100 jours avant d'aller voir Soke (Takeda Sensei) pour me pr&eacute;parer &agrave; pratiquer avec lui.  Lorsque j'ai &eacute;t&eacute; le voir, j'ai &eacute;t&eacute; chanceux car il venait de d&eacute;missionner de son emploi tout juste avant mon arriv&eacute;e.  Nous avions un entra&icirc;nement &agrave; deux le matin, de 5 heures du matin &agrave; 8 heures, puis une pause jusqu'au midi, puis une autre s&eacute;ance &agrave; deux apr&egrave;s le d&icirc;ner jusqu'en soir&eacute;e.  Puis il y avait un cours de soir avec d'autres &eacute;l&egrave;ves.                            Le premier matin, je suis arriv&eacute; au dojo &agrave; 5hres et Sensei &eacute;tait d&eacute;j&agrave; pr&eacute;sent.  Donc le deuxi&egrave;me jour, j'ai d&eacute;cid&eacute; d'arriver 15 minutes plus t&ocirc;t, &agrave; 4h45, pour y &ecirc;tre avant Takeda Sensei. Comme de fait, je suis arriv&eacute; au dojo &agrave; 4h45 et Soke &eacute;tait d&eacute;j&agrave; l&agrave;.  Donc, le jour suivant, je me suis pr&eacute;sent&eacute; &agrave; 4h15 afin d'arriver avant Soke, j'en retirais une certaine fiert&eacute;.  Par contre, je suis arriv&eacute; &agrave; 4h15 et Soke &eacute;tait encore l&agrave; avant moi.  Je ne savais pas pourquoi, mais cela s'est poursuivi jusqu'&agrave; ce que nous commencions &agrave; nous entra&icirc;ner &agrave; 3h du matin.  &agrave; un certain moment, la femme de Takeda Sensei est venue me voir et m'a dit: 'tu ne peux pas arriver au dojo avant Soke, il a besoin de ce temps pour s'entra&icirc;ner et c'est le seul moment o&ugrave; il peut pratiquer par lui-m&ecirc;me avant d'enseigner. '"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:111
msgid ""
"When training with Soke, I was never allowed to throw or apply\n"
"                a technique on him, I was always the uke in our one on one training.\n"
"                Takeda Sensei taught me by doing the techniques on me over and\n"
"                over again. This was very hard on me at first, can you be uke\n"
"                for 1 hour? One on one? But it was 3 hours in the morning and\n"
"                more after lunch! In the evening Soke had a class with other students,\n"
"                and I got to practice and apply techniques on others that I learned\n"
"                during the day with Soke."
msgstr "Lorsque je pratiquais avec Soke, je n'avais jamais le droit de le projeter ou d'effectuer une technique sur lui, j'&eacute;tais toujours le uke, dans nos pratiques &agrave; deux.  Takeda Sensei m'a enseign&eacute; en me faisant subir les techniques sans arr&ecirc;t.  C'&eacute;tait tr&egrave;s difficile pour moi au d&eacute;but, pouvez-vous &ecirc;tre uke pendant une heure?  Un &agrave; un?  Mais c'&eacute;tait trois heures le matin et encore apr&egrave;s le d&icirc;ner!  En soir&eacute;e, Soke avait un cours avec d'autres &eacute;l&egrave;ves, et je pouvais pratiquer et essayer les techniques que j'avais apprises durant la journ&eacute;e avec Soke sur d'autres &eacute;l&egrave;ves."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:119
msgid ""
"After the third day with Takeda Sensei, I started to feel the\n"
"                toll of the training, because it was so severe since I was always\n"
"                the uke. But although growing quiet weary, I decided I was there\n"
"                to train and persevered, and in a short time I got used to this\n"
"                kind of training. Practicing with Soke, I was given permission\n"
"                to teach the Takumakai up to the nikajo level, sixty techniques."
msgstr "Apr&egrave;s le troisi&egrave;me jour avec Takeda Sensei, j'ai commenc&eacute; &agrave; ressentir les effets de l'entra&icirc;nement, parce qu'il &eacute;tait tr&egrave;s dur puisque j'&eacute;tais le uke.  Mais m&ecirc;me si j'&eacute;tais tr&egrave;s fatigu&eacute;, j'ai d&eacute;cid&eacute; que j'&eacute;tais l&agrave; pour apprendre et j'ai pers&eacute;v&eacute;r&eacute; et en une courte p&eacute;riode de temps, je me suis habitu&eacute; &agrave; ce type d'entra&icirc;nement.  En pratiquant avec Soke, on m'a donn&eacute; la permission d'enseigner les techniques du Takumakai jusqu'au niveau nikkajo, soixante techniques"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:125
msgid ""
"At the time we were about 15 students at Soke's dojo, some of\n"
"                the known names being: Arisawa Sensei, Kato Sensei, Saito Sensei,\n"
"                the sempai was Akimoto Sensei who passed away at the age of 85."
msgstr "&Agrave; ce moment, nous &eacute;tions environ 15 &eacute;l&egrave;ves au dojo de Soke.  Quelques-uns des noms connus &eacute;taient: Arisawa Sensei, Kato Sensei et Saito Sensei.  Le sempai &eacute;tait Akimoto Sensei qui d&eacute;c&eacute;da &agrave; l'&acirc;ge de 85 ans."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:129
msgid "How many years did you train with Takeda Tokimune Sensei?"
msgstr "Pendant combien d'ann&eacute;es vous &ecirc;tes-vous entra&icirc;n&eacute; avec Takeda Tokimune Sensei?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:130
msgid "13 years."
msgstr "13 ans. "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:132
msgid "Sensei, you also learned Ono Ha Itto Ryu from Takeda Sensei?"
msgstr "Sensei, vous avez aussi appris le Ono Ha Itto Ryu de Takeda Sensei?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:133
msgid ""
"That's correct. I was one of only six people to be taught\n"
"                Itto Ryu by Soke. He chose to teach it only to people with a good\n"
"                heart, because through kenjutsu you can better understand jujutsu."
msgstr "Effectivement.  J'&eacute;tais une des six personnes &agrave; qui Soke avait appris le Itto Ryu.  Il choisit de ne l'enseigner qu'&agrave; des gens de coeur car &agrave; travers le kenjutsu, on peut mieux comprendre le jujutsu."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:137
msgid "When did you receive your certificates from Soke?"
msgstr "Quand avez-vous re&#231;u vos certifications de Soke? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:138
msgid ""
"I recieved the shihan license in Daito Ryu and menkyo\n"
"                in Ono Ha Itto Ryu in 1985 from Takeda Sensei."
msgstr "J'ai re&#231;u ma certification de shihan en Daito Ryu et de menkyo en Ono Ha Itto Ryu en 1985 de Takeda Sensei."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:141
msgid "Sensei how was the Hakuho Kai born?"
msgstr "Sensei, comment le Hakuho Kai est-il n&eacute;? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:142
msgid ""
"When training with Hisa Sensei I felt that there was\n"
"                older body movement involved behind the techniques. And when training\n"
"                with Soke, I saw that he absolutely did not do any kind of turning\n"
"                and always moved in one line, many of his students were making\n"
"                turns and circles and did not do the techniques how Soke would\n"
"                do them. For example many would jump, or rise into ippon dori\n"
"                instead of releasing (Sensei demonstrates). From watching Soke\n"
"                I knew this was not correct, I followed closely how Takeda Sensei\n"
"                would move and researched the techniques. At the time I was with\n"
"                the Takumakai and taught these things to my own branch dojo. With\n"
"                time it became a difficult situation because other people were\n"
"                doing and teaching techniques in a different way, and did not\n"
"                have the same idea. Even before Takeda Sensei passed away, there\n"
"                were already disputes about who will be the next Soke, and about\n"
"                this license and that license. Takeda Sensei did not want to have\n"
"                any part of this and did not want me involved in it either. He\n"
"                told me to stay out of all the politics, and told me to go on\n"
"                my own and not stay with an organization. He wanted me teach the\n"
"                techniques he taught me. With his encouragement I decided to form\n"
"                the Hakuho Kai."
msgstr "Lorsque je pratiquais avec Hisa Sensei, je sentais qu'il y avait des mouvements corporels plus anciens derri&egrave;re les techniques.  Et lorsque je pratiquais avec Soke, j'ai vu qu'il ne faisait absolument aucune sorte de pivot et ne bougeait toujours qu'en ligne droite, plusieurs de ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves effectuaient des pivots et des cercles et n'ex&eacute;cutaient pas les techniques de la mani&egrave;re que Soke les faisait.  Par exemple, plusieurs sautaient ou s'&eacute;levaient dans ippon dori au lieu de lib&eacute;rer (Sensei fait la d&eacute;monstration).  &agrave; force d'observer Soke, je savais qu'il manquait quelque chose, j'ai suivi avec attention la mani&egrave;re dont Takeda Sensei se d&eacute;pla&#231;ait et j'ai approfondi les techniques.  &agrave; l'&eacute;poque, j'&eacute;tais avec le Takumakai et j'enseignais ces choses dans mon propre dojo affili&eacute;.  Avec le temps, c'est devenu une situation difficile parce que d'autres personnes effectuaient et enseignaient les techniques d'une autre mani&egrave;re, et n'avaient pas la m&ecirc;me conception que moi.  M&ecirc;me avant que Takeda Sensei ne d&eacute;c&egrave;de, il y avait d&eacute;j&agrave; des conflits &agrave; propos du successeur de Soke et &agrave; propos de cette certification et de celle-l&agrave;.  Takeda Sensei ne voulait pas se m&ecirc;ler de tout cela et ne voulait pas que je ne m'en m&ecirc;le non plus.  Il me dit de rester loin de toute cette politique et me dit d'aller de l'avant par moi-m&ecirc;me et de ne pas rester avec une organisation.  Il voulait que j'enseigne les techniques qu'il m'avait montr&eacute;es.  Avec cet encouragement, j'ai fond&eacute; le Hakuho Kai."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:163
msgid ""
"Sensei how did you research the techniques and develop\n"
"                your method of teaching?"
msgstr "Sensei, comment avez-vous approfondi les techniques et d&eacute;velopp&eacute; votre m&eacute;thode d'enseignement? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:165
msgid ""
"I watched very closely how Soke moved, he was always\n"
"                moving in hitoemi, one line. I looked at old paintings of the\n"
"                bushi, their bodies were also always partrayed as being in a hitoemi\n"
"                position because that is how the bushi moved. I read old history\n"
"                texts about life in old Japan and how things worked back them.\n"
"                Across all of this I did not find anything in particular, but\n"
"                there were hints here and there. Then, when researching the techniques,\n"
"                we had pictures (Asahi News pictures taken by Hisa Takuma when\n"
"                Takeda Sokaku was teaching there) of the beginning of a technique\n"
"                and the end of a technique, but could not make certain techniques\n"
"                work. I asked myself why have a technique that doesn't work? So\n"
"                by applying my knowledge from Soke and my research, applying hitoemi\n"
"                and gravity principles I could make those techniques effective\n"
"                and efficient."
msgstr "J'ai observ&eacute; attentivement comment Soke se d&eacute;pla&#231;ait, il se d&eacute;pla&#231;ait toujours en hitoemi, une ligne.  J'ai aussi regard&eacute; de vieux portraits de bushi, leurs corps &eacute;taient aussi toujours dispos&eacute;s dans une position de hitoemi parce que c'&eacute;tait comment ils se d&eacute;pla&#231;aient.  J'ai lu des vieux livres d'histoire &agrave; propos de la vie dans le Japon m&eacute;di&eacute;val et comment les choses se faisaient &agrave; l'&eacute;poque.  &agrave; travers tout cela, je n'ai rien trouv&eacute; de particulier, mais il y avait des indices ici et l&agrave;.  Puis, lorsque j'approfondissais les techniques, nous avions des photos (les photos du Asahi News qui avaient &eacute;t&eacute; prises par Hisa Takuma au moment o&ugrave; Takeda Sokaku y enseignait) du d&eacute;but et de la fin de la technique, mais nous ne pouvions pas en faire fonctionner quelques-unes.  Je me suis demand&eacute; pourquoi certaines techniques ne fonctionnaient pas.  Alors, en appliquant mes connaissances que j'avais apprises de Soke et de mes propres recherches, j'ai appliqu&eacute; le Hitoemi et les principes de la gravit&eacute; et j'ai r&eacute;ussi &agrave; rendre les techniques efficaces et efficientes."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:180
msgid ""
"Sensei, what does 'Hakuho Kai' mean, and why did you chose\n"
"                this name?"
msgstr "Sensei, que veut dire 'Hakuho Kai' et pourquoi avez-vous choisi ce nom? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:182
msgid ""
"Translated 'Hakuho' means 'white phoenix'. You see in\n"
"                Japan's history there were a lot of different eras, like the 'Edo'\n"
"                era, the 'Meiji' era and so on.... If you go back through history,\n"
"                there was an era called 'Hakuho'. It was a time when the Japanese\n"
"                decided to stop outside influence from coming into Japan, it was\n"
"                an era when Japanese were protecting Japanese culture from outside\n"
"                influence. I want to preserve Daito Ryu in it's traditional form\n"
"                and keep the old movements of the bushi behind the techniques,\n"
"                and to not let modern body movement influence it. This is why\n"
"                I chose the name Hakuho Kai."
msgstr "Traduit, 'Hakuho' veut dire 'phoenix blanc'. Vous savez, dans l'histoire du Japon, il y avait plusieurs p&eacute;riodes diff&eacute;rentes, comme l'&egrave;re Edo, l'&egrave;re Meiji et ainsi de suite&#133;  Si l'on remonte le cours de l'Histoire, il y eut une &eacute;poque appel&eacute;e 'Hakuho'.  C'&eacute;tait l'&eacute;poque o&ugrave; les Japonais ont d&eacute;cid&eacute; de bloquer toute influence de l'ext&eacute;rieur, c'&eacute;tait une &eacute;poque o&ugrave; les Japonais d&eacute;fendaient la culture japonaise des influences ext&eacute;rieures.   Je veux pr&eacute;server le Daito Ryu dans sa forme traditionnelle et conserver les anciens mouvements des bushi qui sont &agrave; l'origine des techniques, et de ne pas laisser les mouvements corporels modernes venir les influencer.  Voil&agrave; pourquoi j'ai choisi le nom Hakuho Kai."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:193
msgid "How was Hisa Sensei as a person?"
msgstr "Comment &eacute;tait Hisa Sensei en tant qu'individu? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:194
msgid ""
"His was a very interesting person. He liked to try many\n"
"                news things. For example learned how to fly and airplane, and\n"
"                played golf when it was not as popular as now. He enjoyed life\n"
"                and was a very good, kind man."
msgstr "Il &eacute;tait une personne tr&egrave;s int&eacute;ressante. Il aimait essayer beaucoup de nouvelles choses.  Par exemple, il a appris &agrave; piloter un avion et &agrave; jouer au golf avant que &#231;a ne devienne populaire.  Il aimait profiter de la vie et c'&eacute;tait une tr&egrave;s bonne personne."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:199
msgid "How was Takeda Tokimune Sensei as a person?"
msgstr "Comment &eacute;tait Takeda Tokimune Sensei en tant qu'individu? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:200
msgid ""
"He had a very good heart. After the war, Soke was a\n"
"                police officer and later became a detective. He was a very suspicious\n"
"                person, always suspicious of every one so this must have helped\n"
"                him being a detective. He probably inherited some of these traits\n"
"                from his father, Takeda Sokaku."
msgstr "Il avait un tr&egrave;s grand coeur.  Apr&egrave;s la guerre, Soke a &eacute;t&eacute; policier et plus tard un d&eacute;tective.  Il &eacute;tait une personne tr&egrave;s m&eacute;fiante, toujours m&eacute;fiant &agrave; l'endroit de tout le monde, alors &#231;a doit l'avoir aid&eacute; pour &ecirc;tre un bon d&eacute;tective.  Il a probablement h&eacute;rit&eacute; ces traits de son p&egrave;re, Takeda Sokaku."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:206
msgid "Did Soke speak a lot about his father? Tell many stories?"
msgstr "Est-ce que Soke parlait beaucoup de son p&egrave;re? A-t-il cont&eacute; plusieurs histoires?"

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:207
msgid ""
"Soke never called his father by saying 'father', he\n"
"                always refered to him as Takeda Sokaku. He did not really think\n"
"                of him as a father. When Soke was 10, 11 years old, Takeda Sokaku\n"
"                was approaching 70 years of age. Soke learned kenjutsu from his\n"
"                mother until 5 years old, and after the age of 5 he learned from\n"
"                his father. Takeda Sokaku trained him very hard, he did not have\n"
"                techniques to teach specifically to children. He would have Soke\n"
"                attack him with a sword, he would disarm Tokimune and the sword\n"
"                would go flying into the snow. So at 5 years old Soke would have\n"
"                to go searching through the snow with his bare hands for the sword,\n"
"                pick it up and attack his father. Once again the sword would fly\n"
"                into the snow, and it went on again and again. So this is just\n"
"                and example of how Takeda Sokaku would treat and train his son.\n"
"                It was difficult for Soke to think of him as his father. One day\n"
"                Takeda Sokaku was sleeping, and Soke wanted to put a cover over\n"
"                him to keep him warm. Sokaku, always being in a state of awerness,\n"
"                even when sleeping, grabbed his dagger and went to stab Soke in\n"
"                heart just as Soke was about to put the cover over Sokaku. Soke\n"
"                was barely quick enough to move to the side, got off the line\n"
"                and the dagger that was going for his heart stabbed him in the\n"
"                shoulder. Afterwards Takeda Sokaku scolded his son severely. Saying:\n"
"                ' What kind of a fool are you?! You should never carelessly come\n"
"                up one someone by surprise, it is your fault that you were stabbed;\n"
"                if you would have been aware I would not have cut you!' That's\n"
"                the kind of man Takeda Sokaku was so it must have had an effect\n"
"                on Soke, so he did not feel as Sokaku being his father."
msgstr "Soke n'a jamais appel&eacute; son p&egrave;re 'p&egrave;re', il s'y r&eacute;f&eacute;rait toujours comme Takeda Sokaku.  Il ne pensait pas beaucoup &agrave; lui comme d'un p&egrave;re.  Lorsque Soke avait 10 ou 11 ans, Takeda Sokaku avait presque 70 ans.  Soke appris le kenjutsu de sa m&egrave;re jusqu'&agrave; l'&acirc;ge de 5 ans et ensuite de son p&egrave;re.  Takeda Sokaku l'entra&icirc;na tr&egrave;s fort, il n'avait pas de techniques &agrave; enseigner sp&eacute;cifiquement aux enfants.  Il demandait &agrave; Soke de l'attaquer avec un sabre, il d&eacute;sarmait Tokimune et le sabre &eacute;tait envoy&eacute; loin dans la neige.  Donc &agrave; 5 ans, Soke devait aller trouver son sabre dans la neige avec ses mains nues, le ramasser et attaquer &agrave; nouveau son p&egrave;re.  Puis, l'&eacute;p&eacute;e &eacute;tait renvoy&eacute;e dans la neige et cela &eacute;tait r&eacute;p&eacute;t&eacute; continuellement.  Ceci n'est qu'un exemple comment Takeda Sokaku traitait et entra&icirc;nait son fils.  Il &eacute;tait difficile pour Soke de le voir comme un p&egrave;re.  Un jour, Takeda Sokaku dormait et Soke voulait le recouvrir d'une couverture pour le garder au chaud.  Sokaku, toujours en &eacute;tat de pleine conscience de son environnement, m&ecirc;me durant le sommeil, prit son poignard et faillit poignarder Soke en plein coeur juste au moment o&ugrave; Soke allait lui mettre sa couverture.  Soke a tout juste eu le temps de faire un pas de c&ocirc;t&eacute;, de se retirer de la ligne et le poignard qui allait le frapper au coeur le frappa &agrave; l'&eacute;paule.  Par la suite, Takeda Sokaku r&eacute;primenda s&eacute;v&egrave;rement son fils.  Il lui dit : ' quel genre de fou es-tu? Tu ne devrais jamais t'approcher de fa&#231;on insouciante de quelqu'un par surprise, c'est de ta propre faute si tu t'es fait poignarder; si tu avais &eacute;t&eacute; pleinement conscient, je ne t'aurais pas poignard&eacute;! ' C'&eacute;tait le genre de personne que Takeda Sokaku &eacute;tait, donc s&ucirc;rement que cela a eu son effet sur Soke.  C'est pourquoi il ne le voyait pas comme son p&egrave;re."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:234
msgid "Did Soke use dan rankings when teaching?"
msgstr "Est-ce que Soke utilisait le classement des dan lorsqu'il enseignait? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:235
msgid ""
"Yes, Takeda Sensei used the dan ranking system that\n"
"                originally comes from judo. He a gave out other licenses like\n"
"                the menkyo and shihan license I have. Takeda Sensei also gave\n"
"                two kyuoju dairi, one to Suzuki Sensei and Minamo Sensei, who\n"
"                have both passed away. When giving dan grades, in reality Soke\n"
"                never gave past fifth dan."
msgstr "Oui, Takeda Sensei utilisait le syst&egrave;me de classement des dan qui venait &agrave; l'origine du judo.  Il a aussi donn&eacute; d'autres certifications telles que le menkyo et shihan que je poss&egrave;de d'ailleurs.  Takeda Sensei a aussi donn&eacute; deux kyoju dairi, une &agrave; Suzuki Sensei et une &agrave; Minamo Sensei, qui sont tous les deux d&eacute;c&eacute;d&eacute;s.  Lorsqu'il desservait ses rangs de dan, en r&eacute;alit&eacute; Soke n'en a jamais accord&eacute; un sup&eacute;rieur &agrave; la 5&egrave;me."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:242
msgid "Sensei are dan rankings used in Hakuho Kai?"
msgstr "Sensei, est-ce que le classement par dan est utilis&eacute; dans le Hakuho Kai? "

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:243
msgid ""
"That's correct, we use the dan ranking system. It is\n"
"                important to note that permission to teach is not the same thing\n"
"                as a rank. In Hakuho Kai one must have a good heart and good intentions\n"
"                to have permission to teach."
msgstr "Oui, nous employons le syst&egrave;me des dan.  Il est important de noter que la permission d'enseigner n'est pas la m&ecirc;me que de poss&eacute;der un rang.  Dans le Hakuho Kai, on doit poss&eacute;der un grand coeur et de bonnes intentions pour pouvoir avoir la permission d'enseigner."

#: application/views/scripts/articles/interview-with-okabayashi-sensei.phtml:248
msgid "How many Hakuho Kai dojo are there Sensei?"
msgstr "Sensei, combien de dojos du Hakuho Kai existe-t-il? "

